00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:28.970
to your ownership
in the company.

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:32.710
So my background is I was a
graduate from Sloan in '91.

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:36.080
That was the inaugural
year-- oh, well, in 1990

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:38.810
was the inaugural year
of the $10K Contest.

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:40.510
Well, it's now the $100K.

00:04:40.510 --> 00:04:42.400
And we were the
third place team.

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.370
So rather than get,
you know, I think

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:47.720
it's now $20,000 or $30,000
worth of free legal service

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:51.040
and accounting
service, we got $300

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:53.940
to split between
the three of us.

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:56.510
So since that wasn't enough
to start our business,

00:04:56.510 --> 00:04:59.220
we all went our separate ways.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:00.890
But what I did,
Joe introduced me

00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:03.780
to some guys who had
an interesting idea

00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:07.514
for some network
monitoring equipment.

00:05:07.514 --> 00:05:09.180
And they didn't really
know how to build

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:10.670
a business around that.

00:05:10.670 --> 00:05:14.970
And that experience
in the $10K Contest

00:05:14.970 --> 00:05:18.700
was critical, because I'd
worked with these two guys.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:23.100
And we'd sat at the-- we didn't
have Wi-Fi at that time--

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:24.990
so we're sitting in
the computer lab,

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:28.540
plugging it into a
spreadsheet late at night,

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:33.030
going, well, if we increase
the sales price by this much,

00:05:33.030 --> 00:05:34.470
what does it do to our business?

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:36.657
If we are able to reduce
cost by this much,

00:05:36.657 --> 00:05:37.990
what does it do to our business?

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:40.580
How many salespeople
are we going to need?

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:42.460
And I went through
that whole exercise

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:48.830
of building that template for
the business plan contest.

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:52.770
And because of that, I
had tremendous credibility

00:05:52.770 --> 00:05:53.660
when I started.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:56.280
I knew what I was talking
about when I went in

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:59.610
to talk to these guys who
had this data communications

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:00.610
product.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:02.800
And I was able to
convince them that I could

00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:04.170
help them build their model.

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:07.730
And sure enough, I
was able to do that.

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:09.767
But it was the entering
into the contest,

00:06:09.767 --> 00:06:11.350
and working with the
team, and working

00:06:11.350 --> 00:06:14.830
through all of that, that
helped give me that experience.

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:17.630
The company was
NetScout Systems.

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:21.300
We completed several
rounds of venture financing

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:24.780
there, and went public in 1999.

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:26.626
I then got involved
with a dot.com

00:06:26.626 --> 00:06:29.770
company, which fortunately
didn't last too long.

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:35.120
And then was at a
Homeland Security

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:38.630
company that made bomb detection
equipment for airports.

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:43.450
So completely different
industry, but the same metrics.

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:45.010
The same tools apply.

00:06:45.010 --> 00:06:48.930
The same spreadsheet that
I'd built to get NetScout

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:51.500
off the ground was
the same spreadsheet

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.810
that I used to get
Reveal off the ground.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:56.080
And it's the same spreadsheet
that you guys can all

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:58.060
use to get your
business off the ground.

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:02.320
I raised $125 million in
more than 10 transactions

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.800
over that period.

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:07.540
So you're probably
saying to yourself,

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:10.320
I'm too busy to
do my financials.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:10.860
Right?

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:13.040
I've got more
important things to do.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.200
One, they're not going
to be right anyway.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:17.190
I mean, who can
sit here and say,

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:20.390
we're going to be able to be
spot on on our financials?

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:22.180
Right?

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:25.727
The second is, the VCs aren't
going to believe it anyway.

00:07:25.727 --> 00:07:27.310
They're going to
look at your numbers,

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:29.500
and they're going
to say, they've

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:32.610
got their own ideas of this.

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:35.080
And the third is, you've got
more important things to do.

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:37.890
Building the team, figuring
out what the product is,

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:41.140
and looking at who
your customers are.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:43.680
But the reality
is the financials

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:47.820
are the scoreboard, the
scorecard for your company.

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:51.220
So if you don't know
what you're shooting for,

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:53.360
then how do you know
whether you're making

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:55.920
progress against those goals?

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:57.470
But the more important
thing is kind

00:07:57.470 --> 00:07:59.860
of what I was
talking about with me

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:02.970
and my team in the $10K Contest.

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:06.930
It helps you understand what
your key assumptions are,

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:10.910
because you've got to put those
assumptions into either numbers

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:12.200
or formulas.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.600
You've got to understand
what the drivers are.

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:18.340
So if you're able to
increase prices by 10%,

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:19.360
what does that do?

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:21.360
Is that an important
lever or not?

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:24.500
Or is it more important
to get your costs down?

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:28.180
Or is it more important to
outsource your development

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:31.790
and get your R&amp;D spending down?

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:36.210
Is it more important to do
software as a service model,

00:08:36.210 --> 00:08:37.760
or sell it is a product?

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:40.690
And how do those things
impact how much cash

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:41.580
you're going to need?

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:48.660
So it's a great exercise that
helps you understand what's

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:50.860
going on in your business.

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:53.990
Because as the CEO
of your company,

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:56.060
the number one
job is to maintain

00:08:56.060 --> 00:08:58.360
the cash in the company.

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:00.080
It's the oxygen supply.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:04.350
And without that, you could be
doing everything else right,

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:06.490
but it doesn't take
long for people

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:08.000
to start walking
out the door when

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.680
they're not getting a paycheck.

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:11.160
Now, your management
team-- we've

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:13.670
had those days where I
have to go to the guys

00:09:13.670 --> 00:09:16.380
and say, hey, guys, there's
not going to be anything

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:17.920
in the envelope this week.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.050
But for your rank
and file employees,

00:09:20.050 --> 00:09:22.290
you can't be missing payroll.

00:09:22.290 --> 00:09:25.510
And your vendors will only
let you stretch out payables

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:26.260
for so long.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:32.400
So you've got to know where
you stand with your cash,

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.430
and what cash you need.

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:36.290
So you don't need
to be an accountant,

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:39.370
but you've got to
understand these key terms.

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:41.120
And you've got to be
able to discuss them.

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:44.960
Because the investors
up here, they also

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:46.950
don't expect you to
be an accountant.

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:49.980
But they do expect you
to understand the drivers

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:54.430
in your business, and what the
key metrics in your business

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:54.930
are.

00:09:57.600 --> 00:09:59.260
In Reveal Imaging--
Reveal Imaging

00:09:59.260 --> 00:10:01.900
was a company that made
bomb detection equipment.

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:04.350
And there we had an
all-star management team.

00:10:04.350 --> 00:10:09.210
We had five guys-- this
was founded in 2003,

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:13.050
18 months after 9/11--
we had five guys who'd

00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:16.565
been in Homeland Security
for more than a decade each.

00:10:16.565 --> 00:10:17.940
So there were a
lot of people who

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:22.774
wanted to get into Homeland
Security on September 12, OK?

00:10:22.774 --> 00:10:24.190
But there were not
a lot of people

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:27.720
who were in Homeland Security,
the Homeland Security business,

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:29.060
on September 10.

00:10:29.060 --> 00:10:31.250
And we had five of
those guys here.

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:33.650
So we had a market opportunity.

00:10:33.650 --> 00:10:39.490
The Congress had said,
all passenger bags

00:10:39.490 --> 00:10:42.500
that go on a passenger
airliner in the United States

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:44.710
have to be screened
for explosives.

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:47.680
And we want a machine that
can automatically do that.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:49.900
We don't want people
looking at X-ray images.

00:10:49.900 --> 00:10:52.090
And there were
machines on the market.

00:10:52.090 --> 00:10:54.980
These guys had actually--
of the eight machines that

00:10:54.980 --> 00:10:56.940
had been certified--
these guys had

00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:59.930
been involved in getting four
of those machines certified.

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:02.270
So we really had
an all-star team.

00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:04.510
They had come up with an
idea for a product that

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:07.890
was half the size of
the existing equipment.

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:11.620
Also half of the throughput,
but half of the cost.

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:15.280
And so those metrics were very
compelling for the smaller

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:19.340
airports like Burlington,
Vermont, or Nantucket, Mass,

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:21.920
rather than the Logan's.

00:11:21.920 --> 00:11:25.430
But there's 500 airports in
the country, and one by one

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:27.760
they were getting ticked
off by our competitors.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.770
So we had an opportunity
to get to market

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:33.410
that we had to get to fast,
because once those airports

00:11:33.410 --> 00:11:37.000
were staffed with our
competitors' equipment,

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.040
they were no longer
an opportunity.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:41.470
So we went out, and we
hit the ground running.

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:46.500
And we started raising money
the first day we got together

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:47.770
as a management team.

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:51.880
We raised an angel round within
90 days of $1 million dollars.

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:54.830
And then, within six months, we
raised our first venture round.

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:59.810
And it was a $5 million,
but it was in two tranches.

00:11:59.810 --> 00:12:03.200
The tranches were a
$5 million tranche,

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:08.410
and a second $5 million tranche,
based upon hitting milestones.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:11.760
Because we wanted to raise
as much money as possible,

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:15.170
but our investors were reluctant
to give us everything up front.

00:12:15.170 --> 00:12:16.990
So we reached this
compromise, where

00:12:16.990 --> 00:12:19.630
we said, OK, we're going
to hit some milestones,

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:21.850
and because we had
the financial plan,

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:24.950
and we knew how far $5
million would take us,

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:29.480
we knew what we could get done
before we ran out of money.

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:33.700
And so we were able
to pre-negotiate

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:39.830
an increase in value upon
hitting that milestone.

00:12:39.830 --> 00:12:43.360
So it was kind of a
win-win, because we did not

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:46.130
have to spend-- once we
raised the $5 million,

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:49.110
we didn't have to immediately
start thinking about raising

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:51.270
the next $5 million,
because we had

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:54.510
that kind of in our hip pocket.

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:56.970
All I can say is that,
as soon as we raised

00:12:56.970 --> 00:12:58.760
a round of financing,
I started thinking

00:12:58.760 --> 00:13:01.640
about the next financing
that we were going to do.

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:03.480
It could have been
bank financing,

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:06.270
like an equipment
line, which is simply

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:11.680
as you buy equipment for
your manufacturing facility,

00:13:11.680 --> 00:13:16.190
or as you buy computers for
your software engineers,

00:13:16.190 --> 00:13:20.150
you send a copy of the
invoice over to the bank,

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:23.250
and they will provide--
they will give you

00:13:23.250 --> 00:13:29.730
90% of that money back-- and
you now have a loan to the bank.

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:32.860
So it didn't look like a
lot of money, $500,000.

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:36.530
But as we were getting close
to running out of money,

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:38.410
and we hadn't met
that milestone there

00:13:38.410 --> 00:13:42.420
we had committed to to
get the second $5 million,

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:45.400
that $500,000 was
very important to us.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:50.270
Because that gave us an
extra three months of runway

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:51.920
to get closer to the goal.

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:59.680
So I'm going to kind of
take you behind the scenes

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:03.000
to think about what does
a venture capitalist want.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.840
When they put in
their money, they're

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:10.200
interested in getting 3x
to 5x absolute returns.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:14.080
So if they put $1 million
into your company,

00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:17.810
they want to get $3
million back to $5 million

00:14:17.810 --> 00:14:20.060
back, on top of the $1 million.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:24.370
So they've got to get $4
million to $6 million back.

00:14:24.370 --> 00:14:27.800
And if it's $5
million, do the math.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:31.140
Their investment horizon
is five to seven years.

00:14:31.140 --> 00:14:37.900
And what I will say is that,
when you take venture money,

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:41.540
that clock starts ticking
the day that that money gets

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:43.450
wired into your account.

00:14:43.450 --> 00:14:50.690
And while five years
seems like forever,

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:55.720
the investors realize that five
years goes by in a heartbeat.

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:58.500
And they will start
pounding you to run

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.780
faster than you think you can
possibly run from day one.

00:15:02.780 --> 00:15:07.150
And it's motivating,
and it's a great thing.

00:15:07.150 --> 00:15:09.100
And if you have
the right partners,

00:15:09.100 --> 00:15:11.360
they're helping you
do the right things.

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:13.400
But you got to
recognize that it's

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:16.080
going to be-- I think they
admitted up here-- it's

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:18.730
going to be a very
intense environment when

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:19.650
you take that money.

00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:26.410
So you better be prepared for
it when you take the money.

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:29.080
They also want to get--
I mean, you heard up here

00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:31.410
that they want to get a
significant amount of money

00:15:31.410 --> 00:15:31.910
invested.

00:15:31.910 --> 00:15:33.300
It depends on the firm.

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:35.390
Some firms might want
to put in $1 million,

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:38.100
some firms might want
to put in $5 million.

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:39.291
It depends on the firm.

00:15:39.291 --> 00:15:41.040
But they want to have
a significant amount

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:43.240
of money invested.

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:45.360
And they want to have a
significant ownership.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:49.051
So if $5 million
is their target,

00:15:49.051 --> 00:15:50.550
they don't want to
put in $5 million

00:15:50.550 --> 00:15:52.890
and get 10% of the company.

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:56.780
They want to have-- at an
early stage investment--

00:15:56.780 --> 00:15:59.720
they want to have a
significant amount.

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:02.430
So the formula to think
about how much equity

00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:07.420
you have to give up is
the percentage of equity

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:09.730
that the venture
capitalists are going to get

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:12.030
is the money that they
invest-- and we'll

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:14.720
have some examples on
the next page-- divided

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:19.091
by the pre-money value plus
the money that they invested.

00:16:19.091 --> 00:16:20.090
Now, that's the formula.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:23.000
It doesn't really give you
the answer, because what's

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:24.380
the pre-money valuation?

00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:31.460
But as you heard up here, kind
of where is the market today,

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:33.600
he was saying he sees
a lot of companies

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:39.030
in the $3 million to $6
million pre-money range, right?

00:16:39.030 --> 00:16:43.780
So there is kind of a sense
of where the market is today,

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:47.600
and what other
companies are getting.

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:51.440
But where that pre-money
valuation comes in,

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:56.347
that's the key to
the negotiation

00:16:56.347 --> 00:16:57.180
that you have to do.

00:16:57.180 --> 00:17:00.650
The other part is how much
money they're investing.

00:17:00.650 --> 00:17:04.640
So if we look at a
couple of examples here.

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:08.680
Say a Series A round, $5
million invested on a $5 million

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:10.170
pre-money.

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:14.000
So we take the $5 million
invested, we add that

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.400
to the pre-money of $5 million.

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:18.609
It's 5 over 10, it
comes out to 50%.

00:17:18.609 --> 00:17:20.960
If there's a Series B,
let's say it's $10 million

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:23.530
invested on a $15
million pre-money.

00:17:23.530 --> 00:17:29.090
That'd be $10 million over 10
plus 15, would be 10 over 25,

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:30.480
or 40%.

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:34.950
But recognize that when the
Series B money comes in,

00:17:34.950 --> 00:17:39.820
the Series A investors get
diluted by the same 40%

00:17:39.820 --> 00:17:42.060
that everyone else
gets diluted by.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:46.700
And I have an example
walking through that.

00:17:46.700 --> 00:17:48.530
Typically, the A
and the B investors

00:17:48.530 --> 00:17:49.980
are going to be the same people.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:53.500
So the B investors are kind
of diluting themselves.

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:56.260
But recognize that
that dilution happens.

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:59.190
So don't think that you're
giving up 50% of your company,

00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:00.920
and then 40% of your
company, and you're

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:03.170
left with 10% of your company.

00:18:03.170 --> 00:18:09.790
You're really left with
30% of your company, right?

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:14.670
So if an investor is looking
for three to five times

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:18.060
on their money, and
they've put $15 million in,

00:18:18.060 --> 00:18:26.100
and they own 70% of
the company, then

00:18:26.100 --> 00:18:31.730
three times the $15 million
invested is $45 million,

00:18:31.730 --> 00:18:34.100
plus the original
$15 million back,

00:18:34.100 --> 00:18:35.820
so they've got to
get $60 million.

00:18:35.820 --> 00:18:37.700
They own 70% of the company.

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:43.980
So that company has to be valued
at $85 million to $130 million

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:47.480
for them to get
that type of return.

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:51.640
And so in order to
get so that valuation,

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:56.240
you've got to grow your
revenues to $40 to $60 million.

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:59.940
So there's a lot of
businesses that you guys

00:18:59.940 --> 00:19:04.680
could start that can grow to--
you know, another comment you

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:07.640
heard here was make
sure that your investors

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:11.230
and your opportunity and
your investment dollars

00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:12.430
are aligned, right?

00:19:12.430 --> 00:19:14.660
One of the big
problems was people

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:19.920
going after what turned out to
be a small opportunity with too

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:21.460
much capital.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:24.970
So the problem is, is that
once someone has $15 million

00:19:24.970 --> 00:19:31.970
invested in your company, you've
got to go after the big return.

00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:34.380
So you could have
a business that

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:36.090
could be a great
business for you

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:39.780
and a couple of your MIT
pals that goes to $5 million

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:43.310
in revenue, or $10
million in revenue,

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:46.630
and there's three of you,
and you each own 33%,

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:50.135
and you have no outside income,
and no outside investors,

00:19:50.135 --> 00:19:51.300
and it's very profitable.

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:54.330
It could be a
great business that

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:56.430
could be just a
gold mine for you,

00:19:56.430 --> 00:19:59.790
but it would not be an
appropriate investment

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:01.900
for some of our panelists here.

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:04.540
And if they had come
in as an investor,

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:09.530
then there's going to be a
mismatch, and a lot of tension.

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:15.770
Because you can't get to a
happy place for both of you.

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:19.180
So I know that this screen's a
little bit hard to read here,

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:22.070
but let me just walk you
real quickly through.

00:20:22.070 --> 00:20:26.420
If you've got a
founding group here

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:30.350
that has four million shares
between all of the founders,

00:20:30.350 --> 00:20:34.870
they've got 100% of the equity,
and there's 100% right there.

00:20:34.870 --> 00:20:40.410
You then bring in some early
employees and give them--

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:41.910
and there'd be a
list, I have a list

00:20:41.910 --> 00:20:45.490
in the back of showing kind
of who would get what--

00:20:45.490 --> 00:20:46.980
but you have some
early employees,

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:49.890
and maybe some advisors,
that get a number of shares.

00:20:49.890 --> 00:20:52.930
And so already the founders
get diluted a little bit.

00:20:52.930 --> 00:20:54.580
They then bring
in an angel round

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:58.720
of $500,000 at a $4.5
million pre-money.

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:02.600
So we know for our formula,
$500,000 divided by $5 million,

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.290
the angel investors
are going to get 10%.

00:21:05.290 --> 00:21:10.040
In this case, and in all these
cases, new shares are issued.

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:13.080
The founders continue to own
their four million shares,

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:15.790
but now there's five million
shares in the company,

00:21:15.790 --> 00:21:20.050
and the founders have
been diluted to 80%, OK?

00:21:20.050 --> 00:21:25.390
We now have kind of the
classic A round venture

00:21:25.390 --> 00:21:28.360
capitalists come in, and
they put in $5 million

00:21:28.360 --> 00:21:31.170
at the $5 million that
I talked about earlier.

00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:32.930
They get 50%.

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:34.980
But one of the
things that is going

00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:37.190
to happen when the
A round comes in

00:21:37.190 --> 00:21:38.720
is the investors
are going to want

00:21:38.720 --> 00:21:40.930
to see that you
have an option pool

00:21:40.930 --> 00:21:46.480
so that you can issue stock
options to your employees.

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:49.540
Because all employees
like stock options,

00:21:49.540 --> 00:21:55.110
and it provides extra
incentive to your employees.

00:21:55.110 --> 00:21:57.760
But the investors
are saying, we don't

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:03.100
want to be diluted for the
first 100 people that you hire.

00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:05.990
So you've got to
set aside options

00:22:05.990 --> 00:22:10.270
to take care of those people
without them being diluted.

00:22:10.270 --> 00:22:14.460
So they still get their 50%, but
you've got to create this pool.

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:16.690
And in my example, it's 12%.

00:22:16.690 --> 00:22:22.970
But it's somewhere in the
10% to 20% range, right?

00:22:22.970 --> 00:22:28.110
And that's a topic for
discussion and negotiation

00:22:28.110 --> 00:22:29.530
with your venture capitalists.

00:22:29.530 --> 00:22:33.490
Anything I'm saying wrong
here, feel free to hop in.

00:22:33.490 --> 00:22:37.420
So then we have our final
round is that $10 million

00:22:37.420 --> 00:22:40.950
at $15 million, and
these investors get 40%.

00:22:40.950 --> 00:22:44.640
Notice the A investors
are now down to 30%,

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:48.340
and our founding team
is down to 18.2%.

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:50.960
So this kind of walks you
through the progression

00:22:50.960 --> 00:22:56.720
of how stock gets distributed
to both employees,

00:22:56.720 --> 00:22:59.900
angel investors, and
venture capital investors.

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:00.802
Yep?

00:23:00.802 --> 00:23:04.176
AUDIENCE: So the question I
have is other than the stock

00:23:04.176 --> 00:23:06.104
distribution, do
they get more control

00:23:06.104 --> 00:23:08.514
because they ask for
more seats on the board?

00:23:08.514 --> 00:23:11.888
Is that something which happens
a lot when the second round

00:23:11.888 --> 00:23:13.840
and third round happens?

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:16.610
CHARLIE TILLETT: So the question
is, do they-- so first off is

00:23:16.610 --> 00:23:20.040
the investors are going to
get preferred shares that

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:24.780
have many more rights than
the common shares, OK?

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:27.240
And there will be
anti-dilution provisions,

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:29.010
there will be
ratchet provisions,

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:30.500
in case there's a down round.

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:33.900
But probably the most important
thing that will always happen

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:37.150
is that they will get
board representation.

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:42.480
And that is a little
bit of a negotiated--

00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:46.080
it's not negotiated that they
have board representation,

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:49.150
but what I've seen is, so let's
say that you're the founder,

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:51.690
you say we have two
seats, the founders

00:23:51.690 --> 00:23:54.750
have two seats on the board,
your venture capitalists

00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:56.590
come in, they get two
seats on the board,

00:23:56.590 --> 00:23:58.700
and then you agree that
the fifth board member

00:23:58.700 --> 00:24:02.530
will be mutually agreed upon.

00:24:02.530 --> 00:24:07.860
And you've got to
figure out-- again,

00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:12.140
if you have problems
deciding on a mutually

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:17.430
agreeable fifth board member at
this stage in the relationship,

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:19.900
then these are not the
right venture guys for you

00:24:19.900 --> 00:24:21.400
to be working with, OK?

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:23.420
So it should be pretty
easy to find someone

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:27.520
that everyone agrees
has domain knowledge,

00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:32.520
has expertise in the field, is
entrepreneurial, and is going

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:35.674
to be kind of neutral, right?

00:24:35.674 --> 00:24:37.090
So does that answer
your question?

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:37.370
Yep?

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:39.869
AUDIENCE: Yeah, on a previous
slide, you were talking about,

00:24:39.869 --> 00:24:42.200
say you've taken $10
million in VC money,

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:44.132
but it turns out the
opportunity was smaller.

00:24:44.132 --> 00:24:46.547
It's only $5 million
in revenue per year.

00:24:46.547 --> 00:24:48.310
What are the
options, then, there?

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:49.810
CHARLIE TILLETT:
So her question is,

00:24:49.810 --> 00:24:52.101
let's say you've taken more
money than the opportunity.

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:59.200
There's really no
happy ending there,

00:24:59.200 --> 00:25:02.570
because the investors
are going to want

00:25:02.570 --> 00:25:04.280
to get their money back.

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:07.720
And a company that
grows to $5 million,

00:25:07.720 --> 00:25:11.010
it's kind of the
walking dead, right?

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:12.670
So you're now
making enough money

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:14.870
to where you're not
going out of business,

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:19.470
but there's another problem
there, is that companies that

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:25.690
only get to $5 million and $10
million-- now, I don't know,

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:28.800
how much revenue does
Pinterest-- you know,

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:32.050
there's a lot of companies
out there that have no revenue

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:33.490
and have tremendous valuations.

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:37.750
But let's not plan that we're
going to catch lightning

00:25:37.750 --> 00:25:39.250
in a bottle, OK?

00:25:39.250 --> 00:25:41.820
So a company that has $5
million to $10 million

00:25:41.820 --> 00:25:46.160
in revenue, the reality is that
there's a very small market.

00:25:46.160 --> 00:25:48.780
Who's going to buy
a company like that?

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:51.650
When we were at Reveal
Imaging, we grew the company

00:25:51.650 --> 00:25:55.860
to $100 million, and we grew
the company to $50 million

00:25:55.860 --> 00:26:01.460
in revenue, but our buyers were
aerospace defense companies

00:26:01.460 --> 00:26:03.740
that are huge.

00:26:03.740 --> 00:26:08.450
And they were willing
to pay us $125 million

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:14.070
for $50 million revenue,
but nothing more than that.

00:26:14.070 --> 00:26:18.010
They were only willing to pay
us kind of 1.5 times revenue.

00:26:18.010 --> 00:26:21.160
They were hoping that we would
have $500 million in revenue,

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:24.480
because they were willing
to pay $1.25 billion.

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:27.080
But the problem is that a
$5 million to $10 million

00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:30.600
company doesn't get
any big company who's

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:35.050
your-- it's too small to go
public, and the big companies,

00:26:35.050 --> 00:26:36.870
it's not big enough
to move the needle.

00:26:36.870 --> 00:26:40.450
Especially if you've
already proven that it's not

00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:41.690
going to go like that, right?

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:44.230
You've already decided that
it's going to go $5 million,

00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:45.880
$6 million, $7 million.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:47.625
It doesn't get anyone excited.

00:26:52.472 --> 00:26:56.870
So the business model,
and in my mind-- I mean,

00:26:56.870 --> 00:26:59.860
you heard the term used a
couple of times on the panel

00:26:59.860 --> 00:27:03.700
tonight-- how I think
of it is it's an income

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:05.450
statement in percentage terms.

00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:07.710
And we'll show you some
of the business models

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:12.470
from a number of companies in a
number of different industries.

00:27:12.470 --> 00:27:14.520
But when you think about
your business model,

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:17.610
think about your business
reaching critical mass.

00:27:17.610 --> 00:27:22.280
Do you have to have some kind
of geographic dispersion?

00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:25.630
Or do you need a
critical mass of sales

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:30.400
in order to get your
volume pricing down?

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:32.430
Or maybe it's the
number of customers that

00:27:32.430 --> 00:27:35.070
gives you some kind of synergy.

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:40.900
So when you think about your
business model, think about it,

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:42.920
it's in the happy times, right?

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:45.800
It's reached critical
mass, and it is kind

00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:47.065
of hitting on all cylinders.

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:54.280
So how many are Course 15?

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:58.899
OK, maybe about a
third, or maybe 40%.

00:27:58.899 --> 00:28:00.690
So this is going to be
a little bit boring.

00:28:00.690 --> 00:28:02.650
This section is going to be a
little bit boring for you guys,

00:28:02.650 --> 00:28:04.774
but I want to make sure
everyone's on the same page

00:28:04.774 --> 00:28:05.480
here.

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:08.870
So when we talk about the income
statement, we start at the top.

00:28:08.870 --> 00:28:13.140
And it's your sales number,
also called your revenue number,

00:28:13.140 --> 00:28:17.700
and that's the products that
you're shipping out the door,

00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:19.930
or the service that
you're providing,

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:22.830
and the dollar number that
you're putting on that invoice.

00:28:22.830 --> 00:28:25.680
So it's after any
discounts that you give.

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:28.100
It's after any
kickbacks or anything.

00:28:28.100 --> 00:28:30.675
It's the number-- when
you send out an invoice

00:28:30.675 --> 00:28:33.977
to that customer, what's
the dollar on that invoice,

00:28:33.977 --> 00:28:35.560
and what's the check
that you're going

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:37.390
to get from that customer.

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:41.200
Your cost of goods sold
is the material costs,

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:44.770
the labor it costs to
build your product,

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:48.090
it's the facilities in
which that product is built,

00:28:48.090 --> 00:28:50.710
but it's also your support cost.

00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:54.440
So if you ship a product, and
you have a one year warranty,

00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:58.500
or you have a tech support
line that people are calling,

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:00.370
that's part of your cost, too.

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:02.930
So you've got to staff
that tech support line.

00:29:02.930 --> 00:29:06.440
You've got to man
it, maybe it's 24/7.

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:08.080
If you've got a
hardware product,

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:10.020
and it breaks within
the warranty period,

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:11.440
you've got to fix that.

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:12.880
You've got shipping costs.

00:29:12.880 --> 00:29:15.260
You might have to send
someone out into the field,

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:17.810
if you've got a big machine
like we had at Reveal

00:29:17.810 --> 00:29:20.680
that weighed two tons.

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:22.620
So those are all
the things that go

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:24.020
into your cost of goods sold.

00:29:24.020 --> 00:29:28.670
It's not your R&amp;D. So it's
not your programming cost.

00:29:28.670 --> 00:29:32.069
Your product development
costs go down in R&amp;D.

00:29:32.069 --> 00:29:33.860
Then, you have your
three main departments.

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:36.310
Sales and marketing
is self-explanatory.

00:29:36.310 --> 00:29:38.760
R&amp;D would be all of your
programming, product

00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:41.190
development, any
material that gets

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:45.970
bought as part of your
product development process.

00:29:45.970 --> 00:29:47.680
Then, your general
and administrative

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:49.290
is kind of everything else.

00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:51.890
Your CFO is in there,
your CEO is in there.

00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:57.910
HR, IT, your facilities,
your facility staff

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:00.660
for the non-manufacturing
facility.

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:02.630
And at the bottom is
your operating profit,

00:30:02.630 --> 00:30:07.300
or EBITDA, earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation,

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:08.360
and amortization.

00:30:08.360 --> 00:30:12.060
And I like to use that as the
yardstick, because it gets

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:15.380
really complicated adding
in capital expenses

00:30:15.380 --> 00:30:19.240
and depreciating stuff, and that
kind of obscures what's really

00:30:19.240 --> 00:30:20.870
going on in your business.

00:30:20.870 --> 00:30:24.590
So I would urge
you in your plans

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:28.790
don't depreciate
anything, and also

00:30:28.790 --> 00:30:31.960
don't start allocating your
general and administrative

00:30:31.960 --> 00:30:34.300
expenses across
other departments.

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:39.110
Just let them sit in your G&amp;A.

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:41.526
So I get a lot of
business plans.

00:30:41.526 --> 00:30:43.400
I'm happy to look at
anyone's business plans.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:45.380
My email is at the end
of this presentation.

00:30:45.380 --> 00:30:48.204
Any time, whether it's part
of this class, or any time

00:30:48.204 --> 00:30:50.620
in the next 10 years, you want
to send me a business plan,

00:30:50.620 --> 00:30:53.030
say, I'm getting ready
to make a presentation.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:54.890
I want someone to
look at this and just

00:30:54.890 --> 00:30:57.970
make sure it's
not totally crazy.

00:30:57.970 --> 00:30:59.350
So I get a lot of
business plans.

00:30:59.350 --> 00:31:02.370
And the first thing that I do
when I look at a business plan

00:31:02.370 --> 00:31:04.740
is I look at the
top line, and say,

00:31:04.740 --> 00:31:08.262
how big is this
business going to get?

00:31:08.262 --> 00:31:10.660
What is the market
opportunity here?

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:12.320
So here's an
opportunity, they think

00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:14.295
it can grow to $75 million.

00:31:14.295 --> 00:31:17.130
The next thing that I
look at is, in year four,

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:21.080
kind of the happy times, once
they've reached critical mass,

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:22.750
what does this
business look like?

00:31:22.750 --> 00:31:24.444
What are the gross margins?

00:31:24.444 --> 00:31:25.860
I've worked in
companies that have

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:29.700
80% gross margins and companies
that have 50% gross margins,

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:32.140
and I can tell you it's
dramatically easier

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:34.490
to make money and
run a business when

00:31:34.490 --> 00:31:39.370
you have 80% gross margins
versus 50% gross margins.

00:31:39.370 --> 00:31:41.230
It's dramatically different.

00:31:41.230 --> 00:31:43.490
And then, where are the
big expenses down here?

00:31:43.490 --> 00:31:45.970
What are they spending on R&amp;D?

00:31:45.970 --> 00:31:47.600
Particularly, what
are they spending

00:31:47.600 --> 00:31:48.980
on sales and marketing?

00:31:48.980 --> 00:31:52.090
Because most firms end up
at about the same place

00:31:52.090 --> 00:31:54.470
in R&amp;D spending once
they reach critical mass.

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:57.740
They end up about the
same place G&amp;A spending.

00:31:57.740 --> 00:32:02.270
But the sales and marketing
wildly varies, depending on

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:05.780
is it a consumer product, is it
a business to business product,

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:07.770
is it a luxury
product that you have

00:32:07.770 --> 00:32:10.590
to do a lot of advertising,
is there a lot of trade shows.

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:14.440
So it depends on your whole
sales strategy and distribution

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:18.650
strategy, and that shows up
in your sales and marketing.

00:32:18.650 --> 00:32:21.810
The last thing that I look at
is kind of the operating profit

00:32:21.810 --> 00:32:23.810
over the this four year period.

00:32:23.810 --> 00:32:26.240
Because that gives you
a pretty good yardstick

00:32:26.240 --> 00:32:28.780
for how much cash
this company is

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:33.130
going to take to get
to profitability.

00:32:33.130 --> 00:32:38.950
It's not perfect, but it's
probably within 20% or 30%,

00:32:38.950 --> 00:32:40.890
which is a good-- you
know, it at least says

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:45.350
to me this company, $3.5
million plus $2.5 million

00:32:45.350 --> 00:32:48.870
is $6 million, maybe it lost a
little bit here in year three,

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:49.850
so it's $7 million.

00:32:49.850 --> 00:32:52.964
It's not a company that's
going to need $20 million.

00:32:52.964 --> 00:32:54.380
But it's also not
a company that's

00:32:54.380 --> 00:32:56.004
going to need $1
million or $2 million.

00:32:56.004 --> 00:32:59.810
So it gives you just a sense
of what this company needs.

00:32:59.810 --> 00:33:02.040
Now, let's say you're looking
at your business plan.

00:33:02.040 --> 00:33:03.831
I would urge you to
look at the same thing.

00:33:03.831 --> 00:33:08.590
Start at the top line,
and say, do I really

00:33:08.590 --> 00:33:11.400
think this business can
do this kind of revenue?

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:14.810
I would also urge you to look
at year four or year five,

00:33:14.810 --> 00:33:16.290
whatever it's going
to take you get

00:33:16.290 --> 00:33:19.470
to that place, the
critical mass, and say,

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:22.950
does this business model
look like other companies

00:33:22.950 --> 00:33:25.740
in my space, or is it different?

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:28.490
And if it's different, that
doesn't mean it's wrong.

00:33:28.490 --> 00:33:31.970
It just means that you better
understand why it's different.

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:34.260
Maybe you're doing something
dramatically different.

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:36.360
Maybe you've got
some tremendous cost

00:33:36.360 --> 00:33:42.920
of goods sold value that
other companies don't have.

00:33:42.920 --> 00:33:46.100
But you've got to
understand that.

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:50.110
Then, I would urge you to
think about a year one,

00:33:50.110 --> 00:33:53.530
because thinking about
expenses in year four

00:33:53.530 --> 00:33:58.050
is a very difficult exercise.

00:33:58.050 --> 00:34:00.630
Because you can't even--
I mean, here you are,

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:02.600
you're getting your
business off the ground.

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:07.910
It's hard to think about if
I had $75 million in revenue,

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:09.409
where would that money be spent.

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:12.659
But it's very easy to think
about the next 12 months.

00:34:12.659 --> 00:34:14.710
And who are my key hires?

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:17.020
And how much are those
people going to cost?

00:34:17.020 --> 00:34:18.820
And what are the
stuff that they're

00:34:18.820 --> 00:34:21.260
going to need to buy to
help them do their job?

00:34:21.260 --> 00:34:23.780
And you're probably not
going to have a lot of sales,

00:34:23.780 --> 00:34:25.530
so you don't really
need to think too much

00:34:25.530 --> 00:34:27.880
about cost of goods sold yet.

00:34:27.880 --> 00:34:28.620
OK?

00:34:28.620 --> 00:34:30.500
But you need to
start thinking about

00:34:30.500 --> 00:34:33.570
what are my staffing
priorities, and what

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:36.480
are the things that we need,
and where are we going to locate

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:39.070
our business, and what we don't
have to spend on facilities,

00:34:39.070 --> 00:34:40.440
and that kind of thing.

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:44.570
And then, while year one
should be fairly easy to do,

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:47.120
year two is not that much
more of a stretch, because you

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:50.590
are ready have kind of thought
about where I am in month 12.

00:34:50.590 --> 00:34:52.630
And so you just kind
of extrapolate that

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:56.550
into what are we going to do
once we start having revenue?

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:59.620
OK, so what is my support
team going to look like?

00:34:59.620 --> 00:35:02.070
What is my sales team
going to look like?

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:03.890
And put some numbers on that.

00:35:03.890 --> 00:35:05.460
And then, once you've
done that, look

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:08.750
at where your percentages
are out here in year two.

00:35:08.750 --> 00:35:12.470
And you already looked at
where they are in year four.

00:35:12.470 --> 00:35:16.884
And kind of make year three as
kind of a blending process, OK?

00:35:16.884 --> 00:35:19.050
Now, you're not going to
do this on an annual basis.

00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:21.360
I'm going to urge you to
do it on a quarterly basis.

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:23.760
And we'll get into those
specific spreadsheets

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:26.080
and talk you talk you
through that in a bit.

00:35:29.110 --> 00:35:37.540
So the business model in terms
of this percentage of income,

00:35:37.540 --> 00:35:41.060
