Say R&amp;D is in that
same 10% to 15%.

00:39:53.250 --> 00:39:55.510
And the revenue per
employee at Microsoft

00:39:55.510 --> 00:39:57.430
is about the same as Cisco.

00:39:57.430 --> 00:40:00.670
Oracle and SAP,
which are more peers,

00:40:00.670 --> 00:40:03.720
have very similar
revenue per employee

00:40:03.720 --> 00:40:08.790
in that $250,000
to $300,000 range.

00:40:08.790 --> 00:40:12.562
The internet companies
are all across the board.

00:40:12.562 --> 00:40:14.520
I mean, Apple's not really
an internet company,

00:40:14.520 --> 00:40:17.900
but they are kind
of interesting here

00:40:17.900 --> 00:40:22.660
in that they have $2 million
of revenue per employee.

00:40:22.660 --> 00:40:23.610
Mind-boggling.

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:27.210
I mean, Google is at $1 million.

00:40:27.210 --> 00:40:29.750
I started putting Google on
this after they went public.

00:40:29.750 --> 00:40:32.490
And I said, well, they
can't sustain that.

00:40:32.490 --> 00:40:34.230
They were about $1
million when I first

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:35.740
did it I think three years ago.

00:40:35.740 --> 00:40:39.510
And they've actually increased
their revenue per employee

00:40:39.510 --> 00:40:40.230
as they've grown.

00:40:40.230 --> 00:40:42.550
So they've become
more productive,

00:40:42.550 --> 00:40:45.940
which is kind of-- few
companies are able to do that.

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:47.900
Usually, companies
have a decrease

00:40:47.900 --> 00:40:50.320
in revenue per employee
as they get bigger.

00:40:50.320 --> 00:40:52.880
Google's been able
to increase it.

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:55.250
Again, here, R&amp;D spending.

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:58.931
I mean, Apple is so big that
that 2% is still a huge number,

00:40:58.931 --> 00:40:59.430
right?

00:40:59.430 --> 00:41:02.490
But if we look at
the rest of these,

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:04.000
it is a little bit
across the board,

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:08.350
and it's part of where a company
is in this stage of their life

00:41:08.350 --> 00:41:09.810
cycle.

00:41:09.810 --> 00:41:12.679
But this gives you kind of a
sense of where companies are.

00:41:12.679 --> 00:41:14.220
Another thing that's
interesting here

00:41:14.220 --> 00:41:16.680
is the two companies with
the lowest gross margin

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:20.970
are Apple, which is
selling hardware,

00:41:20.970 --> 00:41:23.580
and Pandora, which
is selling music.

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:27.900
So just because you're in a
intellectual property business,

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:32.670
or in a-- I don't know what you
would call music, if you're not

00:41:32.670 --> 00:41:34.120
calling it hardware.

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:38.140
But it's kind of interesting
that their cost of goods

00:41:38.140 --> 00:41:41.280
are actually as high as Apple's,
because of the royalties

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:42.670
that they have to pay.

00:41:42.670 --> 00:41:46.484
And that creates some
problems for them.

00:41:46.484 --> 00:41:48.400
I think they're now
starting to show a profit,

00:41:48.400 --> 00:41:50.115
but it's still a
very tough business.

00:41:53.560 --> 00:41:56.170
Looking at business models
over a period of time,

00:41:56.170 --> 00:41:57.670
they evolve slowly.

00:41:57.670 --> 00:42:00.230
I've been doing this
talk since at least '98.

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:07.730
And just looking at Cisco,
it looks like the same.

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:10.380
I mean, yeah, it goes up
and down a little bit.

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.520
But companies do
not dramatically

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:15.120
change over a period of
time once they kind of

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:17.600
hit that critical mass.

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:23.530
So as you're
building your model--

00:42:23.530 --> 00:42:27.010
I know the talk yesterday was
on your product and pricing

00:42:27.010 --> 00:42:31.470
your product-- what's the value
that you bring to the customer?

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:38.240
And how is that value
going to be split

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:40.270
between you and the customer?

00:42:40.270 --> 00:42:41.730
I hear a lot of
people say, well,

00:42:41.730 --> 00:42:46.980
we have a product that will
save our customers $10,000.

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:50.060
So we think we should
charge them $10,000.

00:42:50.060 --> 00:42:52.380
Well, at $10,000,
they're indifferent

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:54.520
whether they do it manually
or whether they do it

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:56.640
with your new
piece of equipment.

00:42:56.640 --> 00:42:59.260
So you've got to
price that product

00:42:59.260 --> 00:43:04.040
to where it's compelling for
the customer to take that risk

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:05.600
and make that change.

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:09.190
And if it's a $10,000
value to them,

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:13.580
you've probably got to price
that at $2,000 or $3,000,

00:43:13.580 --> 00:43:17.670
and let them capture the
majority of that savings,

00:43:17.670 --> 00:43:19.890
because they're taking the risk.

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:21.920
And so you've got
to figure out how,

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:24.050
at a $2,000 or
$3,000 price, you're

00:43:24.050 --> 00:43:27.280
going to be able to sell
that and capture enough value

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:29.980
yourself, OK?

00:43:29.980 --> 00:43:33.140
Your distribution strategy.

00:43:33.140 --> 00:43:36.690
So think about the price, and
then your cost of goods sold

00:43:36.690 --> 00:43:39.010
should be pretty
straightforward.

00:43:39.010 --> 00:43:41.370
I mean, you know the
material that goes in there.

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:43.680
Again, it's not how
long is it going to take

00:43:43.680 --> 00:43:45.140
to develop this product.

00:43:45.140 --> 00:43:48.660
That's part of your R&amp;D, and
that's a whole other exercise.

00:43:48.660 --> 00:43:54.010
But it's, if I sell a unit, how
much material goes into it, how

00:43:54.010 --> 00:43:57.400
much labor goes into
it, how much overhead

00:43:57.400 --> 00:44:00.310
in the manufacturing
facility goes into it,

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:02.570
how much support am I
going to have to provide?

00:44:02.570 --> 00:44:06.110
These are all questions that,
if you sit there and noodle away

00:44:06.110 --> 00:44:11.932
at it, you can come up with
a pretty reasonable range,

00:44:11.932 --> 00:44:14.820
and come up with your
cost of goods sold.

00:44:14.820 --> 00:44:16.966
When you think about your
distribution strategy,

00:44:16.966 --> 00:44:18.590
how am I going to
sell my product, that

00:44:18.590 --> 00:44:20.850
could have-- I have an
example of that in here--

00:44:20.850 --> 00:44:26.220
that could have a huge impact
on everything involving

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:30.130
your business, in both your
revenue all the way down

00:44:30.130 --> 00:44:32.530
to your sales and marketing
and your operating profit.

00:44:32.530 --> 00:44:35.100
So that's a huge decision
you're going to have to make.

00:44:35.100 --> 00:44:38.110
R&amp;D, I would argue, should
end up at the 10% to 20%

00:44:38.110 --> 00:44:39.880
range generally.

00:44:39.880 --> 00:44:41.620
As we've looked at
a lot of companies,

00:44:41.620 --> 00:44:42.920
that's where they end up.

00:44:42.920 --> 00:44:46.470
That doesn't mean you shouldn't
be at 30%, like Zynga was,

00:44:46.470 --> 00:44:49.550
depending on where you
are in your life cycle.

00:44:49.550 --> 00:44:52.060
But if you're a
technology company,

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:58.080
and you're not spending
10% of your revenue on R&amp;D,

00:44:58.080 --> 00:45:01.210
you're yourself short for
tomorrow's products, right?

00:45:01.210 --> 00:45:03.540
Because you've always
got to be evolving.

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:06.110
G&amp;A is going to end
up at 5% to 15%.

00:45:06.110 --> 00:45:09.950
The lower you can
get that, the better.

00:45:09.950 --> 00:45:13.210
That's where the CFO is,
so just squeeze that down.

00:45:13.210 --> 00:45:16.400
And make sure you build
in an operating profit.

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:21.770
Now, you're operating profit
shouldn't be 40% to 50%.

00:45:21.770 --> 00:45:24.360
There's a few companies
that can get away with that.

00:45:24.360 --> 00:45:26.910
But to think that your
company is one of those

00:45:26.910 --> 00:45:30.360
is probably unrealistic.

00:45:30.360 --> 00:45:36.140
So if you're putting
together your model,

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:40.174
and you keep coming up with a
40% to 50% operating profit,

00:45:40.174 --> 00:45:42.340
you should really question
some of your assumptions.

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:45.390
Do I really, am I
missing anything here?

00:45:45.390 --> 00:45:47.780
I'm not saying it's wrong.

00:45:47.780 --> 00:45:49.500
It might be doable.

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:52.860
But you're going to get
some pushback on that

00:45:52.860 --> 00:45:56.780
from people who've looked
at a lot of business plans.

00:45:56.780 --> 00:46:00.520
So I talked about how
your distribution strategy

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:03.260
is going to impact
your operating profit.

00:46:03.260 --> 00:46:04.970
So let's look at an
example here where

00:46:04.970 --> 00:46:07.220
you're selling it through
your own direct sales force.

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:09.590
You have $100 million in
revenue, your cost of goods

00:46:09.590 --> 00:46:11.880
is $40 million, leaving
you with $60 million,

00:46:11.880 --> 00:46:13.900
or 60% gross margin.

00:46:13.900 --> 00:46:17.040
You have $23 million in sales
and marketing, $12 million

00:46:17.040 --> 00:46:20.540
in R&amp;D, and some G&amp;A,
bringing your total expenses

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:24.475
to $40 million, and an operating
profit of $20 million, or 20%.

00:46:24.475 --> 00:46:26.100
So let's say, instead
of that, you say,

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:28.290
I'm going to bring
in a distributor,

00:46:28.290 --> 00:46:33.250
and give him a 20% discount off
of our list price or selling

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:34.090
price.

00:46:34.090 --> 00:46:37.814
And in return for that 20%,
he's going to go out and sell it

00:46:37.814 --> 00:46:38.480
to the customer.

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:41.630
He gets to keep the
20%, but he frees me up

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:44.530
of all the sales and
marketing activity.

00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:46.370
Well, not entirely.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:48.760
Because even the
distribution channel

00:46:48.760 --> 00:46:50.360
needs some care and feeding.

00:46:50.360 --> 00:46:53.260
So you can't completely get
rid of your sales force.

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:56.020
You can't completely get rid
of your marketing efforts.

00:46:56.020 --> 00:46:57.270
But you can cut those back.

00:46:57.270 --> 00:46:59.580
And in my example, I said,
well, you could cut it back

00:46:59.580 --> 00:47:02.390
from $23 million to $8 million.

00:47:02.390 --> 00:47:05.050
Now, your R&amp;D is
still going to be

00:47:05.050 --> 00:47:06.810
the same, because
you've got to keep

00:47:06.810 --> 00:47:10.230
feeding the machine with
new products, right?

00:47:10.230 --> 00:47:12.630
And your cost of goods is
going to be exactly the same,

00:47:12.630 --> 00:47:15.190
because you're shipping
the same number of units.

00:47:15.190 --> 00:47:16.810
But because you have
fewer employees,

00:47:16.810 --> 00:47:19.610
you probably don't need
quite as many people in HR,

00:47:19.610 --> 00:47:21.380
you don't need as
many bean counters.

00:47:21.380 --> 00:47:23.720
Your G&amp;A is going to
be a little bit less,

00:47:23.720 --> 00:47:25.500
and so that's going
to be $4 million.

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:30.920
So in this example, your revenue
is reduced from $100 million

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:33.090
to $80 million, and
your operating profit

00:47:33.090 --> 00:47:35.560
is reduced from $20
million to $16 million,

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:38.030
but you're still
getting a 20% profit.

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:43.400
Now, I don't know whether
one is right or wrong.

00:47:43.400 --> 00:47:45.900
I would say that the
distributor model

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:48.790
is going to be great if it
can get you to market faster,

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:52.390
or if it can take you from
$80 million to $160 million

00:47:52.390 --> 00:47:56.030
faster than you could grow
organically from $100 million

00:47:56.030 --> 00:47:57.750
to $160 million.

00:47:57.750 --> 00:47:59.490
You're still getting
the same 20%.

00:47:59.490 --> 00:48:06.230
And whether that 20%
came out at 15% or 25%,

00:48:06.230 --> 00:48:08.990
the more important number
here is the $16 million

00:48:08.990 --> 00:48:12.300
in operating profit
versus the $20 million

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:15.600
in operating profit.

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:17.470
So as you're
building your model,

00:48:17.470 --> 00:48:19.560
there is some business
planing software out there,

00:48:19.560 --> 00:48:20.560
kind of like a TurboTax.

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:23.080
It asks you a
bunch of questions.

00:48:23.080 --> 00:48:25.940
It asks you the questions,
you answer the assumptions,

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:28.630
and it spits out a plan.

00:48:28.630 --> 00:48:31.410
Do not use that software,
because the beauty

00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:34.310
of this exercise, the
benefit of this exercise,

00:48:34.310 --> 00:48:38.880
is understanding exactly
what's going into your model,

00:48:38.880 --> 00:48:40.510
and building it yourself.

00:48:40.510 --> 00:48:47.530
And when something doesn't add
up, figuring out what's broken.

00:48:47.530 --> 00:48:52.080
When you start getting
50% operating profits,

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:58.200
start saying, let's look
at my revenue per employee.

00:48:58.200 --> 00:49:02.190
Oh, my revenue per employee
is $1 million per employee.

00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:05.659
Well, Google does that,
and Apple does that,

00:49:05.659 --> 00:49:07.450
but there are not very
many other companies

00:49:07.450 --> 00:49:10.200
that have $1 million in
revenue per employee.

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:15.910
So maybe I need to add more
employees to my staffing plan.

00:49:15.910 --> 00:49:20.740
And where am I going to
deploy those people in order

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:23.790
to build up my organization?

00:49:23.790 --> 00:49:26.910
So it's doing it, it's
working the exercise

00:49:26.910 --> 00:49:29.870
that is the real benefit.

00:49:29.870 --> 00:49:35.420
Build your sales projections
from the bottom up.

00:49:35.420 --> 00:49:38.000
Anyone watch Shark Tank?

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:38.880
OK.

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:41.651
I gave this talk
about two months ago,

00:49:41.651 --> 00:49:43.900
and everyone said, no, it's
on Friday night, I go out.

00:49:43.900 --> 00:49:46.240
You know, I'm not waiting
at home Friday night.

00:49:46.240 --> 00:49:48.210
So someone was on
Shark Tank last week,

00:49:48.210 --> 00:49:50.580
and they said they're
selling a product that

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:52.090
went into school lockers.

00:49:52.090 --> 00:49:56.080
And they said, why are
you valuing your company

00:49:56.080 --> 00:49:57.040
at $5 million?

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:01.570
And he said, well, there's
50 million school lockers

00:50:01.570 --> 00:50:05.170
in the country, and we only
need to get 5% of them.

00:50:05.170 --> 00:50:10.810
I mean, it's a crazy-- that's
wrong on so many counts.

00:50:10.810 --> 00:50:12.917
Because it doesn't
talk about how

00:50:12.917 --> 00:50:15.250
you're going to get into each
school, how many are going

00:50:15.250 --> 00:50:18.920
to sell into each school, what
is your distribution strategy

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:20.090
to get there.

00:50:20.090 --> 00:50:22.790
So instead of saying,
the market is huge

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:24.650
and we're going to
get a slice of it,

00:50:24.650 --> 00:50:26.600
what you said need
to say is, we're

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:28.590
going to have five sales guys.

00:50:28.590 --> 00:50:30.330
And each sales
guy is going to be

00:50:30.330 --> 00:50:32.760
responsible for a
territory in the country.

00:50:32.760 --> 00:50:35.750
And each territory has--
I'm kind of making this up

00:50:35.750 --> 00:50:37.780
about the school
lockers as I go here--

00:50:37.780 --> 00:50:41.860
but each territory
has 25,000 schools.

00:50:41.860 --> 00:50:45.320
And I expect each sales
guy to higher 10 reps.

00:50:45.320 --> 00:50:48.460
And each rep is going to
go to two schools a day.

00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:55.040
And we expect a closure rate of
10% when they go to a school,

00:50:55.040 --> 00:51:00.670
and each school that buys these
is going to buy 50 lockers.

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:02.610
And you put that
all in, and it'll

00:51:02.610 --> 00:51:05.230
come up with a model for how
many you're going to sell.

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:10.320
And that may not be--
it will not be accurate.

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:13.554
Because as you put this
together, it's a crystal ball.

00:51:13.554 --> 00:51:14.970
And when you get
out there, you're

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:19.730
going to find out a sales guy
can't go to two schools a day,

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:24.000
and he can't close 10%,
and they don't buy 50.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:27.540
But when you get a guy
out there selling stuff,

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:29.710
he's going to be
providing data, and you're

00:51:29.710 --> 00:51:32.480
going to start getting
feedback to say,

00:51:32.480 --> 00:51:34.860
we can visit three
schools a day,

00:51:34.860 --> 00:51:37.270
but there's only
a 5% closure rate,

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:40.210
but each school that does
buy is going to buy 75.

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:43.130
And then, you can
adjust your model.

00:51:43.130 --> 00:51:45.040
But since you've
built your model,

00:51:45.040 --> 00:51:48.610
now you can adjust
it, and figure out

00:51:48.610 --> 00:51:50.490
where you're going to go next.

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:54.490
The last thing is that
there's spreadsheet overload.

00:51:54.490 --> 00:51:58.380
So never do a best
case, worst case,

00:51:58.380 --> 00:52:00.550
and present three
different models, and say,

00:52:00.550 --> 00:52:03.000
if everything goes right,
here's what we need.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.990
I'm not saying don't
look at contingencies.

00:52:06.990 --> 00:52:10.320
But just put your
best foot forward.

00:52:10.320 --> 00:52:12.289
Put your best
estimate on the paper.

00:52:12.289 --> 00:52:13.830
Say, here's what we
think we're going

00:52:13.830 --> 00:52:23.430
to do, and leave the best case,
worst case for someone else.

00:52:23.430 --> 00:52:26.110
I might give you some rules of
thumb on the next spreadsheet.

00:52:26.110 --> 00:52:29.730
These are focused on making
your investment interest

00:52:29.730 --> 00:52:30.870
attractive to investors.

00:52:30.870 --> 00:52:33.410
Just like your $5
million business

00:52:33.410 --> 00:52:35.021
might be a great
business, it's not

00:52:35.021 --> 00:52:36.520
going to be attractive
to investors.

00:52:36.520 --> 00:52:39.370
So I may say, don't put
together a business plan that

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:41.189
only gets you to $5 million.

00:52:41.189 --> 00:52:42.480
That could be a great business.

00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:44.720
OK, so don't let me
discourage you from that.

00:52:44.720 --> 00:52:47.770
It's most relevant for
technology companies.

00:52:47.770 --> 00:52:52.050
So if you're going to
start a fast food chain,

00:52:52.050 --> 00:52:54.770
these metrics are not
going to apply to you.

00:52:54.770 --> 00:52:57.710
And like I said, it might
not apply to your industry.

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:04.520
Staffing is what's going
to drive your expenses, OK?

00:53:04.520 --> 00:53:09.720
