00:55:54.720 --> 00:55:58.270
In terms of cash flow, it's
critical to understand it.

00:55:58.270 --> 00:56:01.100
But producing a
cash flow statement

00:56:01.100 --> 00:56:04.260
is really complicated, and
it's really prone to error.

00:56:04.260 --> 00:56:06.090
And the reason is
that you have to put

00:56:06.090 --> 00:56:08.030
in all of these
formulas, and then

00:56:08.030 --> 00:56:12.460
the plug number that makes
all the formulas work is cash.

00:56:12.460 --> 00:56:18.100
So any error in any formula, or
anything that you fat-fingered

00:56:18.100 --> 00:56:22.280
wrong shows up as cash.

00:56:22.280 --> 00:56:24.120
And sometimes it's
to the negative,

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:26.840
sometimes it's to the positive.

00:56:26.840 --> 00:56:28.480
Every time I do
this, I say I'm going

00:56:28.480 --> 00:56:32.140
to put together a cash flow
just so people can look at one.

00:56:32.140 --> 00:56:35.070
And maybe I'll chastise myself,
and I'll go home and do this.

00:56:35.070 --> 00:56:37.200
And if I do, I'll
send it to Joe.

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:40.150
But a good proxy for
cash flow is just

00:56:40.150 --> 00:56:42.150
looking at your
cumulative operating

00:56:42.150 --> 00:56:46.150
losses over the period of
time, and adding in any capital

00:56:46.150 --> 00:56:47.780
expenses that you had.

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:50.030
And while that's
not perfect, it's

00:56:50.030 --> 00:56:52.870
a pretty good number
for how much money

00:56:52.870 --> 00:56:56.670
this business is going to need.

00:56:56.670 --> 00:57:01.200
