01:07:15.170 --> 01:07:18.940
So use as many formulas
in this as you can.

01:07:18.940 --> 01:07:23.480
And so that brings us
back to our quarterly P&amp;L,

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:27.570
and where it all comes together.

01:07:27.570 --> 01:07:30.500
I've got a quick example
here on your CAPEX.

01:07:30.500 --> 01:07:33.050
And so what I did was I
took your total revenues,

01:07:33.050 --> 01:07:36.220
but I offset revenues
by a quarter,

01:07:36.220 --> 01:07:38.590
figuring that
customers are going

01:07:38.590 --> 01:07:41.830
to take 60 to 90 days to pay.

01:07:41.830 --> 01:07:44.520
So if you bill them
now, assume that you're

01:07:44.520 --> 01:07:47.320
going to get money 90
days from now, right?

01:07:47.320 --> 01:07:50.860
And hopefully,
you'll get it sooner.

01:07:50.860 --> 01:07:52.589
But your other expense
is your employees,

01:07:52.589 --> 01:07:53.880
which are 2/3 of your expenses.

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:55.960
They want to get paid
on payday, right?

01:07:55.960 --> 01:07:57.970
They don't want to get
paid 30 days from now.

01:07:57.970 --> 01:07:59.550
So I just assumed--
you know, this

01:07:59.550 --> 01:08:03.180
is a little bit of a
conservative look at it--

01:08:03.180 --> 01:08:08.120
but I assume your other expenses
come due in the current period.

01:08:08.120 --> 01:08:13.170
And so based on that, you plug
in a starting balance here,

01:08:13.170 --> 01:08:17.140
and you say, where does
this money get us to?

01:08:17.140 --> 01:08:22.920
This money gets us
to the end of Q3.

01:08:22.920 --> 01:08:26.180
In that case, I'm going to
need to raise additional money,

01:08:26.180 --> 01:08:29.080
and how much money am I going
to have to raise there to get us

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:30.710
to the next milestone?

01:08:30.710 --> 01:08:32.460
So in this case, I
said, well, maybe we've

01:08:32.460 --> 01:08:34.830
hit a milestone here
at the end of Q3,

01:08:34.830 --> 01:08:36.760
and that's going to
allow us to raise

01:08:36.760 --> 01:08:38.189
our next round of funding.

01:08:38.189 --> 01:08:38.689
OK?

01:08:41.330 --> 01:08:42.890
I've talked about most of these.

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:47.020
Showing steady and
consistent growth.

01:08:47.020 --> 01:08:48.790
And here's some
suggestions in here,

01:08:48.790 --> 01:08:52.010
in terms of an executive summary
versus a full blown business

01:08:52.010 --> 01:08:52.510
plan.

01:08:52.510 --> 01:08:56.046
In reality, the
executive summary

01:08:56.046 --> 01:08:58.045
is all most people are
going to want to look at,

01:08:58.045 --> 01:08:59.858
at the beginning, and
then when they really

01:08:59.858 --> 01:09:01.399
get into due diligence,
they're going

01:09:01.399 --> 01:09:04.390
to want to look at the rest.

01:09:04.390 --> 01:09:07.979
So I think I can get through the
rest of this in five minutes,

01:09:07.979 --> 01:09:11.430
because I've gone
over a lot of it.

01:09:11.430 --> 01:09:14.069
What I would say, as you think
about equity in your company--

01:09:14.069 --> 01:09:18.870
you're sitting around a
conference table here at MIT,

01:09:18.870 --> 01:09:21.220
and you're thinking
about the company,

01:09:21.220 --> 01:09:26.060
or maybe you've been working
on the company for the last two

01:09:26.060 --> 01:09:28.420
years and you're really
ready to launch it--

01:09:28.420 --> 01:09:32.149
all I would urge you is that
the work that is yet to be done

01:09:32.149 --> 01:09:34.990
is far more than the work
that has been done already.

01:09:34.990 --> 01:09:38.240
Even though it feels like
you've done a tremendous amount,

01:09:38.240 --> 01:09:42.050
the work that it takes growing
to a $1 million dollars

01:09:42.050 --> 01:09:42.979
is hard.

01:09:42.979 --> 01:09:45.770
But growing from $1
million to $10 million

01:09:45.770 --> 01:09:48.490
is equally hard, if not harder.

01:09:48.490 --> 01:09:52.750
And going from $10 million to
$100 million is really hard.

01:09:52.750 --> 01:09:56.870
So the fact that a lot
has been accomplished,

01:09:56.870 --> 01:09:59.050
there's still a lot left to do.

01:09:59.050 --> 01:10:03.670
So you don't want to
reward people for what's

01:10:03.670 --> 01:10:04.860
been done in the past.

01:10:04.860 --> 01:10:09.160
You want to incentivize them
to do things in the future.

01:10:09.160 --> 01:10:13.800
So I'm a big believer
that everyone should vest.

01:10:13.800 --> 01:10:15.690
I used to be
adamantly against this

01:10:15.690 --> 01:10:17.740
when I was a member
of a founding team.

01:10:17.740 --> 01:10:20.570
But I've heard horror stories
where three or four people

01:10:20.570 --> 01:10:24.430
get together, and one
guy, or one person,

01:10:24.430 --> 01:10:26.760
gets an opportunity
that they can't pass up

01:10:26.760 --> 01:10:29.880
and they leave with
their 25% of the company.

01:10:29.880 --> 01:10:32.280
And then the three
people that are left

01:10:32.280 --> 01:10:37.080
are now working for
themselves, and not

01:10:37.080 --> 01:10:41.560
taking a paycheck, for someone
who's actually got a great job.

01:10:41.560 --> 01:10:45.670
So I think everyone should vest
over some kind of three or four

01:10:45.670 --> 01:10:47.630
your period.

01:10:47.630 --> 01:10:51.246
Typically, this is the
ranges that you would see.

01:10:51.246 --> 01:10:55.450
A CEO in the 5% range,
5% to maybe 10%.

01:10:55.450 --> 01:10:57.590
VPs in the 1% to 2 and 1/2%.

01:10:57.590 --> 01:11:00.160
This would be after dilution.

01:11:00.160 --> 01:11:04.490
Senior managers about 0.25%, and
a senior individual contributor

01:11:04.490 --> 01:11:06.790
about 0.10%.

01:11:06.790 --> 01:11:12.350
If you're on the
founding management team,

01:11:12.350 --> 01:11:16.560
you might get two to three
times this amount, in part

01:11:16.560 --> 01:11:18.596
because you're going
to get diluted.

01:11:18.596 --> 01:11:20.970
And if you're founding employee,
you might get even more.

01:11:20.970 --> 01:11:26.147
So if you have a senior
individual contributor,

01:11:26.147 --> 01:11:27.730
who's really important
to the company,

01:11:27.730 --> 01:11:31.300
and he's going to get 0.10%,
that's the kind of person you

01:11:31.300 --> 01:11:37.570
might give 0.25%
or 0.50% up front.

